======================================================================

This is necessary because some of the associated `organism_codes` may not be unique, and this change ensures that the correct and unique `organism_codes` are used in all cases.

The changes made to the model include:

* Adding a new scope to the `has_many` association with `organism_codes`, which is called `-> { uniq }`. This scope filters out any duplicate entries in the associated `organism_codes`.
* Changing the `as` option of the `has_many` association with `infection_organisms` to `infectable`, as this is more descriptive of the relationship.

The changes made to the model are necessary to ensure that the correct and unique `organism_codes` are used in all cases, and to avoid any issues related to duplicate entries in the associated `organism_codes`.

Update save-field-ng directive to support destroy event of the scope
--------------------------------------------------------------

The changes in this commit aim to add support for the `$destroy` event of the AngularJS scope, which is triggered when the scope is being destroyed. This allows us to reset the initial value of the field if it was changed and the user navigates away from the page or closes the tab without saving the changes.

The implementation involves adding a new listener for the `$destroy` event on the `scope` object, which will be triggered when the scope is destroyed. In this listener, we check whether the `iAttrs.value` attribute exists and if it does, we assign the initial value to that attribute using the `$parse` service. This ensures that any changes made to the field are discarded when the user navigates away from the page or closes the tab without saving the changes.

This commit also adds a new line of code in the `controller` function, which is responsible for setting up the `onSave` callback. The `onSave` callback will be triggered whenever the user attempts to save the changes made to the field. In this implementation, we are not using the `onSave` callback yet, but it will be used in future commits to handle the saving of the changes made to the field.

def get_commit_message(diff):
    # extract the file path and the changed lines
    file_path = diff['file_path']
    added_lines = diff['added_lines']
    removed_lines = diff['removed_lines']

    # calculate the total number of changes
    total_changes = len(added_lines) + len(removed_lines)

    # create the commit message
    message = f"Update {file_path}: {total_changes} changes"
    if total_changes > 0:
        message += "\n\n"
        message += "".join([f"+{line}\n" for line in added_lines])
        message += "".join([f"-{line}\n" for line in removed_lines])

    return message

Update `copy` action to use resolved file paths for globbed files

This commit updates the `copy` action to use resolved file paths instead of glob patterns when copying files from disk to the store. This is done by using `path.resolve()` to resolve any relative paths in the `fromGlob` pattern and then mapping the resulting array of resolved file paths to an array of absolute file paths.

This change is necessary because the `globby` library returns glob patterns instead of resolved file paths when using the `nodir` option, which can cause issues when copying files from disk to the store. By using absolute file paths, we ensure that the correct files are copied and that any relative path issues are avoided.

Update file provider to support backup option
===========================================

The changes in this commit update the `file` provider to support a new `backup` option. This option allows users to specify whether or not backups should be created when a file is updated. If set to `true`, Chef will create a backup of the file before updating it. If set to an integer greater than 0, Chef will create a backup with that many revisions.

This change was made to allow users more control over how their files are backed up and to improve the overall user experience. The `backup` option can be used in conjunction with other options like `create_if_missing` and `replace_only`.
